properties.name: Yangtsa
properties.desc: The traditional startpoint of the pilgrimage. Buses from Deqin to Cizong stop here, and there is basic accommodation and (horseback) transportation. You may have to book ahead for horses in Deqin.

properties.name: Qunatang
properties.desc: A common stopping-point located at the confluence of two rivers. The Qunatang river (I think Chonating in Tibetan?) is a fast glacial stream which joins the Nujiang/Salween River to flow through Myanmar.

properties.name: Abing
properties.desc: A village of (according to Baidu) 525 people - Tibetan speakers. A large tourist information centre was built here in 2016. The area also has shops, restaurants, and fairly basic accommodation. The village specialises in producing wooden bowls and white radishes.

properties.name: Quzhu
properties.desc: A hot spring area in front of a temple. A police checkpoint here may check foreign travellers suspected of entering Tibet without the necessary permit.

properties.name: Lakangla
properties.desc: A temple by a tributary river of the Nujiang/Salween.

properties.name: Cawalong/Chanan
properties.desc: A small but strategically-appointed town at the intersection between Yunnan, Tibet and Myanmar. This town is not only part of this pilgrimage, but also part of the Tea Horse Road - the perilous old mountain road to Southeast Asia, trading tough Tibetan ponies for Chinese tea.

properties.name: Longpu
properties.desc: Many travellers skip this road, taking a lift straight to Gebu. The little village of Longpu lies at the foot of the Tangdui La Pass.

properties.name: Tangdui La Pass
properties.desc: A 3350m pass on the old Tea Horse Road. The pass itself is not so picturesque, but the views back down the valley to Cawarong are excellent.

properties.name: Gebu
properties.desc: A Tibetan village, reached by passing through the villages of Zhagu and Lada. The Weiqiu River flows next to the village.

properties.name: Gebu La Pass
properties.desc: A steep climb. About an hour before the pass is an accommodation shack and simple food stall. For religious reasons, the pilgrimage is more popular during the Year of the Sheep, but this also brings more litter. This pass is particularly badly-affected.

properties.name: Laide/Ladiza
properties.desc: A very small Tibetan village which serves as a convenient stopping-point for hikers staying in its local-run informal guesthouses.

properties.name: Shuo La Pass
properties.desc: The last and highest mountain pass of the pilgrimage, this is a fearsome two-day uphill climb. The pass marks the pilgrim's return to Yunnan Province.

properties.name: Meilishui
properties.desc: The endpoint of the pilgrimage - an attractive village on the Lancang River, with good views of the summit of Kawagarbo in the distance. It's traditional for pilgrims to keep a hand-cut bamboo staff as a souvenir of their journey.

properties.name: Dokarla Pass
properties.desc: A steep, high pass at 4400m. The border between Tibet and Yunnan is marked with a solid wall of prayer flags; only a single narrow channel permits entry. Small rock shrines at the top provide shelter and material comforts for wandering souls.

properties.name: Deqin
properties.desc:
Deqin ('Deqen' in Tibetan), is a base-camp town which will very likely serve as a gateway to the Meili Snow Mountains area - reachable by bus from Lijiang or Dali to the south. The town itself is nothing special, but the location is spectacular. 
 
This is also probably the best place to hire a guide. This is a good idea, because the mountain is so deadly that a few devout Buddhists may climb Kawagarbo to cut short their lives and bring about their next reincarnation.

properties.name: Yongshitong
properties.desc: A campsite and popular stopping-point for hikers on their first day. The Dokarla Pass awaits pilgrims on the next day.

properties.name: Zansutang
properties.desc: A large camp with a shop, located just after the Dokarla Pass.
